 style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">children’s</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> drama Wolfblood.   However, as Salford is home to </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Children’s</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> and Sport, there is less evidence of f</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">actual programmes on a similar scale being produced in the North.</span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">In terms of radio, the BBC Trust has noted the problems associated with Radio 4 in particular.   As a Northern-based supplier of programmes to Radio 4, City Broadcasting recognizes that Radi</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">o 4 has made considerable efforts to attract Northern audiences – for instance by producing one of this yea</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">r’s Reith Lectures in Liverpool, and our own production, The New North, which explored the way new public cultural buildings in the North have change</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">d perceptions about the region.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">  </span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">However, the gap that needs to be closed to reach Northern audiences requires a substantial and sustained initiative, encouraging the supply of ideas and talent from the North on a greater scale than has been achieved to d</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ate.</span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">This question of portrayal is linked to the question of external suppliers based in the North, which is dealt with in the next section.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">What balance should be struck in what the BBC produces in-house, commissions externally and leaves </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">entirely to others to create?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The balance between in-house and external commissions from a Northern perspective.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">In order to attract more Northern viewers and listeners</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">, it</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> is important for the BBC to have access to a wider pool of ideas and talent from the North.</span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The impact of BBC North has been transformational and is warmly welcomed.   The following proposals reflect an appreciation of what has been achieved and are offer</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ed as a ‘Phase Two’ solution to build on what has already been done.</span><br /><br /><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">TELEVISION:</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">FACTUAL AND OTHER GENRE COMMISSIONING FOR THE NORTH TO SUPPLEMENT DRAMA AND CHILDRENS OUTPUT.</span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> The upturn in drama produced from the North is to be welcomed, the volume of do</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">cumentaries and current affairs coming from the region is lower than it should be given the historic legacy of programmes in those genres.</span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">At MediacityUK the focus on in-house production has been transformational. However, the volume of independently produ</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ced programming from the North remains disappointing – in part because the departments responsible for commissioning</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> programmes at MediacityUK are </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Children’s</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">, Learning and S</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">port.</span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">And even where a potential commissioning department is located at MediacityUK</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-si