 is</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> disappointingly low.   </span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">When the BBC Trust reviewed independent radio supply in 2010 it rejected a 25 percent quota like that in TV.     I</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">stead</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> it opted for a 10% WOCC on top of the 10% quota</span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">For Radio 4 that would be</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> a maximum of 628 potential hours.    According to Radio 4’s figures the total actually commissioned this year is 442 – 14 percent of hours.  </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Although this is in excess of the 1</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">0% baseline, it shows that </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">in-house production units have taken the higher proportion of the contestable hours.</span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">It is interesting to compare this performance against the WoCC with what happens in network TV  -  46% of network TV hours the BBC commissioned </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">from indies in 2011/12.  So radio indies are not competing with their in-house rivals in radio as they are in TV.  </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Does this </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">explain why an independent radio sector seems to have had problems in growing compared with </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">the successful</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> and sustainable independ</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ent </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">TV </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">sector?</span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The competition for a smaller</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> amount of commissions</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> also tends to increase centralizing forces.  According to the information published by the Trust in 2010 in 2009,  70% of Radio 4 indies are based in London and the South – in effect the ma</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">rket for network radio production is divided between big in-house London production units and their London-based independent competitors.</span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">By comparison independents in England accounted for just 12% of the number of companies supplying Radio 4 – out of a t</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">otal of 68 companies supplying Radio 4 that’s just 14 companies for the whole of the rest of England.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Radio 4’s annual spend on independent production is £7m (total Radio 4 budget is £91m).    Almost half of that is spent on the top 10 indies.  This expl</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ains why it is so difficult for an out-of-London radio production sector to develop in the North.</span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">With competition for radio production so intense, the lack of an out</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">of-London quota for independent radio programmes means that the independent sector in the</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> North is particularly exposed to centralizing tendencies when commissioning.</span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">We would support further initiatives such as Radio 4’s Closing the Gap initiative and 5 Live’s kicker funded projects.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">   Ther</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">e could be, for instance</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">, a</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Northern Radio Developmen</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">t F</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">und</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> designed to encourage the production of major Northern-originated ideas – the aim would be to </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">develop</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> programming which would appeal to Northern licence payers who currently </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">feel the</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">y are under-served by the BBC and thereby assist in growing the rad</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">io production sector in the North, so that further programmes could be developed in future.</span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The aim would be to help build a sustainable independent radio companies in the North, although as piecemeal initiatives they would not of themselves be sufficient </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">to address an issue which we believe requires urgent attention.</span><br /><br /><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">RADIO 25% QUOTA</span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">For</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> the </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">independent radio sector as a whole</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> to grow and develop, we would urge a 25% quota for radio </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">across all networks.</span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">It is argued that this would have a disruptive impact</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> on BBC in-house capacity.  However it is widely recognized that the 25% TV quota and subsequent assignment of rights in programmes to independent producers has had a beneficial impact on developing the highly successful UK independent TV sector, and offer</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">s a competitive edge to encourage in-house production.   We do not see why this would not be the case in radio.</span><br /><br /><br /><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">RADIO OUT-OF-LONDON PRODUCTION QUOTA.</span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">A further option could be </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">considered would be </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">to introduce a new 2</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">5% out</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">of-London quota</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> – this is low</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">er than would </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">the 35% quota which was set in order to reach for Channel 4’s regional obligations and remit.  At 25% it ought to be an</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> achievable target reflecting the</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> low baseline from which it will begin.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The aim of such quotas is to provide a solution </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">where there is market failure – the fact that Northern licence fee payers feel underserved by some BBC national networks is we believe not unconnected with the fact that there is so little independently produced production from outside London.</span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Taking Ra</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">io</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> 4 as an example, the volume strands – </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Woman’s</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> Hour, You and Yours –</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> are produced in-hous</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">e by BBC Radio in Salford, and those strands which were tendered, such as Gardeners World, have been won by London-</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">based independents.  We would like to see greater vo</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">lume of production from outside London, but do not think this is likely to happen without the intervention of a quota.</span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Recognising that regional independent production would need to rise rapidly in order to meet a quota of 25% we would suggest it should be</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> phased in over three years, rising to 25%.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">DIGITAL EXTERNAL SUPPLIERS.</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0